library(tidytext)

file_paths <- c(
  "HP1.txt",
  "HP2.txt",
  "HP3.txt",
  "HP4.txt",
  "HP5.txt",
  "HP6.txt",
  "HP7.txt"
)

novels <- tibble(novel = 1:7, text = map_chr(file_paths, read_file))

processed_novels <- novels %>%
  mutate(processed_text = str_to_lower(text)) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, processed_text) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
# 1) Visualize the top 5 words for each novel
word_frequency <- processed_novels %>%
  count(novel, word, sort = TRUE)

top_words <- word_frequency %>%
  group_by(novel) %>%
  top_n(5)
## Selecting by n
top_words %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(word, n), y = n, fill = as.factor(novel))) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~novel, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Word", y = "1Frequency", fill = "Novel") +
  theme_minimal()

# 2) Visualize the top words based on tf-idf
tf_idf <- processed_novels %>%
  count(novel, word) %>%
  bind_tf_idf(term = word, document = novel, n)

top_tfidf_words <- tf_idf %>%
  group_by(novel) %>%
  top_n(5, tf_idf)

top_tfidf_words %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(word, tf_idf), y = tf_idf, fill = as.factor(novel))) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~novel, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Word", y = "2tf-idf", fill = "Novel") +
  theme_minimal()

# 3)Visualize the sentiment scores
sentiment_dictionary <- read.delim("AFINN-111.txt", header = FALSE, sep = "\t", col.names = c("word", "score"))

sentiment_scores <- processed_novels %>%
  inner_join(sentiment_dictionary) %>%
  group_by(novel) %>%
  summarize(sentiment_score = sum(score))
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
sentiment_scores %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(novel), y = sentiment_score, fill = as.factor(novel))) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Novel", y = "3Sentiment Score", fill = "Novel") +
  theme_minimal()

# 4) Visualize the most contributing words
sentiment_contributions <- processed_novels %>%
  inner_join(sentiment_dictionary) %>%
  group_by(novel, word) %>%
  summarize(contribution = sum(score))
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'novel'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
top_contributing_words <- sentiment_contributions %>%
  group_by(novel) %>%
  top_n(5, contribution)

top_contributing_words %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(word, contribution), y = contribution, fill = as.factor(novel))) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~novel, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Word", y = "4Contribution", fill = "Novel") +
  theme_minimal()

Executive summary

The purpose of this text analysis is to analyze the emotional changes in the series of seven Harry Potter novels as examples. The analysis involved several steps, including text preprocessing, frequency analysis, tf-idf calculation, sentiment analysis, and identifying the most contributing words to the sentiment score of each book. The analysis provided valuable insights into the text of the Harry Potter novels, including the most frequently used words, important words in each book, sentiment scores, and the most influential words in determining the sentiment of each novel. You can see the emotional changes throughout the series. It can be seen from the results that with the appearance of the biggest villain, the overall becomes more negative.

Data loading, cleaning and preprocessing

Preprocess the text by removing punctuation, converting to lowercase, and removing stop words.

Text data analysis

Individual analysis and figures

Anaysis and Figure 1

To calculate the five words with the highest frequency in each novel, the frequency of each word was counted using the preprocessed text. The results were then visualized using a bar graph. Each bar represented a novel, and the height of the bar represented the frequency of the corresponding word. Different colors were used for each word to enhance readability and distinguish between the words.

Anaysis and Figure 2

The tf-idf of each novel was calculated using the preprocessed text.The results were then visualized using a bar graph. Each bar represented a novel, and the height of the bar represented the frequency of the corresponding word. Different colors were used for each word to enhance readability and distinguish between the words.

Anaysis and Figure 3

Sentiment analysis was performed using the AFINN Sentiment Dictionary. The dictionary assigns a positive or negative numeric score to each word based on its sentiment. The purpose of this figure was to identify the most positive or negative novel based on the sentiment scores. By visually comparing the sentiment scores, it becomes evident which novel has a more positive or negative sentiment overall.

Anaysis and Figure 4

The contribution of each word to the sentiment score of each book was computed using the sentiment scores obtained from the AFINN Sentiment Dictionary and the word frequency in each novel. The purpose was to provide a visual comparison of the most significant words in each book, allowing readers to quickly identify the distinctive words that contribute to the uniqueness of each novel.
